On Fri, Jan 27, 2012 at 4:48 PM, Sebastien Lambla &lt;seb@...&gt; wrote:
&gt; You introduce coupling to your definition to understand a link.

Yes, this is what link relations are for.

&gt; An atom link expects an identifier, not an identifier template. Same goes
&gt; with rfc5988.
&gt;
&gt; You establish with those known links a relationship between two resources,
&gt; the current one and the resource /blah/{introyourtemplatehere}
&gt;
&gt; Rewriting what identifiers mean (here, from identification to identification
&gt; builder) is shoehorning concepts into one that should not be mucked about
&gt; with (the identifier of a resource).

.. so what are the actual problems you are foreseeing?

Afaict, the worst that will happen is clients are unaware of the
templated nature of the link (implied by the rel) will dereference it
as if it were a plain URI. Is that really a big deal?

&#39;Shoehorning&#39; is one (arguably pedantic) way of looking at it.. I just
look it as sensible re-use of existing mechanisms e.g. you can now
have templated/query links in the Link header for free, same with your
custom rels in Atom.

Cheers,
Mike
